# Documentation Writing Style

## Tone
- Concise and straight to the point — no filler, no fluff
- Direct phrasing ("you can override X via") over explaining internals
- Don't restate what's already obvious from context

## Structure
- One-liners beat paragraphs; bullet lists beat prose when listing options
- Prefer short callout boxes (`<Info>`, `<Note>`, `<Warning>`, `<Tip>`) over full sections for secondary info
- Link to the relevant page instead of repeating details inline
- Drop "this page covers..." preambles — let the content speak
- Remove sections that state the obvious (e.g. "all integrations are enabled by default" when a table already shows it)

## Accordions & Details
- Reference tables (options, arguments, fields) go in `<Accordion>` dropdowns, not inline
- Skip lead-in prose before code in accordions — the title is the context
- Keep accordion content tight: code + short bullets, no paragraphs
- Tips and notes: one line max, action-oriented

## Descriptions
- Runtime modes, shutdown, error handling: one sentence each
- Feature descriptions: what it does, not how it works internally
- BYO/advanced sections: short bullets over paragraphs
